title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.001
frontText: How do you negate a boolean value?
backText: You cannot negate a boolean value, at least not numerically using the minus operator, -. You can invert the boolean value using the logical complement operator.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.002
frontText: Which are immutable: String, StringBuilder, StringBuffer, arrays, or ArrayList?
backText: String is the only immutable class in the list.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.003
frontText: True or false? The first line of every constructor is a call to the parent constructor via the super() command.
backText: False. A method may instead call this() as the first line of the constructor instead of super(), although it will eventually resolve to a constructor that calls super() as its first line.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.004
frontText: What is the difference between super() and super?
backText: The super() command calls the constructor of the parent class and is used in the first line of every child constructor, whereas super is a keyword used to reference a member of the parent class.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.005
frontText: A try statement is allowed to have how many finally blocks?
backText: Zero or one

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.006
frontText: What keyword would be used for a class that extends an interface?
backText: Trick question! A class cannot extend an interface.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.007
frontText: What is 12 % 5 - 1?
backText: 1

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.008
frontText: True or false? The break or continue statement requires a semicolon when used without optional labels.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.009
frontText: What are the default values for these instance variables: String s; int num; boolean b; double d?
backText: s = null; num = 0; b = false; d = 0.0

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.010
frontText: Which of the following variables can null be assigned to? String s; Object o; int num; boolean b
backText: String s and Object o can be assigned null because they are objects. int and boolean are primitives and so cannot be assigned null.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.011
frontText: What characters can a variable name begin with?
backText: A letter, dollar sign ($), or underscore (_)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.012
frontText: What characters may a variable name end with?
backText: A letter, number, dollar sign ($), or underscore (_)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.013
frontText: Are curly brackets, { }, required in if-then statements?
backText: No, they are optional if there is only one statement in the branch of the if statement.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.014
frontText: The bytecode for a class named Hello in the a.b.c package must appear in what directory structure?
backText: The file Hello.class must be in the subdirectory a/b/c.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.015
frontText: What is the most common signature of a main() method?
backText: public static void main(String[] args)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.016
frontText: An instance of a class is called a(n) _________________.
backText: Object

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.017
frontText: What is the command line used to compile the Java class Wolf.java, and what file does it generate?
backText: Run: javac Wolf.java (and it generates Wolf.class)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.018
frontText: What is the command line to run the program contained in Wolf.class?
backText: java Wolf

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.019
frontText: What order do the class declarations, import statements, and package declaration go within a file?
backText: The package declaration comes first, followed by imports, followed by the class declaration.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.020
frontText: What do JDK and JVM stand for?
backText: Java Development Kit and Java Virtual Machine

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.021
frontText: What are the instructions run by the JVM called?
backText: Bytecode

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.022
frontText: What are the three valid formats for comments?
backText: // /* */ and /** */

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.023
frontText: What does JAR stand for?
backText: Java Archive

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.024
frontText: var can be used as the type for which of the following: instance variable, static variable, local variable, constructor parameter, method parameter?
backText: var can be used only as a local variable. It can also be used as an identifier in variable and package names.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.025
frontText: Besides letters and numbers, what symbols are permitted to be used in identifiers?
backText: $ and _

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.026
frontText: Which of the following are reserved words in Java? and, const, goto, foreach, default, xor
backText: const, goto, default

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.027
frontText: True or false? Garbage collection is guaranteed to run at a fixed schedule and when the JVM is low on memory.
backText: False. The JVM controls when garbage collection is run and when it occurs is not guaranteed.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.028
frontText: True or false? Instance initializer blocks run before any constructors are initialized.
backText: True. Fields and instance initializer blocks are run first, in the order they appear, followed by any constructor calls.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.029
frontText: True or false? String is a primitive type.
backText: False. String is an object type, although Java has built‐in support for String literals.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.030
frontText: True or false? At runtime, it is possible to change the type of a var after it is declared.
backText: False. A var is initialized with a specific type. Due to polymorphism, other subtypes may be assigned, but the underlying type cannot be changed.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.031
frontText: What is the syntax for creating an instance initializer?
backText: {} with zero or more statements inside the block

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.032
frontText: Name the eight Java primitive types and indicate which are integer types, which are floating‐point types, and which are neither, in increasing order of size.
backText: In increasing order of size for each group: byte, short, char, int, and long are integer types; float and double are floating‐point types; and boolean is neither.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.033
frontText: What’s the syntax for writing a no‐args constructor?
backText: () { ... }

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.034
frontText: Rank these operators from highest operator precedence to lowest: + (addition) * ! == ++
backText: ++ ! * + ==

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.035
frontText: Which operator decrements a value and returns the new value?
backText: The pre‐decrement operator: --variable

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.036
frontText: What symbols can be used to change the order of operation in Java?
backText: Parentheses, ()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.037
frontText: What is the data type of z? short x = 20; short y = 30; var x = x + y;
backText: int, as all addition operations involving integer values are automatically promoted to int

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.038
frontText: True or false? The logical complement operator, -, flips the value of a boolean expression.
backText: False. The logical complement operator is !.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.039
frontText: Which operator can be used to avoid cast exceptions at runtime?
backText: instanceof

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.040
frontText: True or false? In Java, = and == can both be used to test equality.
backText: False. Only == is a test for equality; as = is the assignment operator.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.041
frontText: What does a short‐circuit operator do, and which ones are available in Java?
backText: A short‐circuit operator skips evaluating the right‐hand side of an expression if the value can be determined by the left‐hand side. Java includes support for and &&.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.042
frontText: Describe the ternary operator, its syntax, and how it can be used for an assignment.
backText: The ternary operator tests a Boolean condition and returns one of two results. It is of the form booleanExpression ? expression1 : expression2. It can be used as a shorthand version of an if‐then‐else statement to assign a value to a variable in a single line.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.043
frontText: Which of the following requires an explicit cast to be assigned to a short value? int, byte, float, bit
backText: int and float require an explicit cast, while byte does not. Note bit is not a primitive type in Java.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.044
frontText: True or false? An if statement can have one or more associated else statements.
backText: False. An if statement can have at most one associated else statement.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.045
frontText: Name the data types supported by a switch statement.
backText: int and Integer, byte and Byte, short and Short, char and Character, String, enum, and var (if the type of the var resolves to one of the other types)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.046
frontText: True or false? A case statement can use effectively final variables.
backText: False. The variables must be compile‐time constants. Unlike effectively final variables, a compile‐time constant must be explicitly marked final and be initialized in the line it is declared.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.047
frontText: Which looping statement guarantees the body is executed at least once?
backText: do {} while ()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.048
frontText: What are acceptable data types in the right side of a for‐each loop?
backText: A built‐in Java array or class that implements java.lang.Iterable

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.049
frontText: True or false? All of the parts of a traditional for loop are optional.
backText: True. For example, the statement for( ; ; ) {} is a valid (infinite) loop.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.050
frontText: Why is not recommended to modify a loop variable in the body of the loop?
backText: It could produce side effects or unexpected results if the loop counter or condition is modified directly.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.051
frontText: Which statement can be used to stop the current loop execution and immediately evaluate the loop condition?
backText: continue

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.052
frontText: True or false? Nested loops can only be used with for loops.
backText: False. Other types of loops, such as while and do while, can be used as nested loops.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.053
frontText: What is the purpose of a label statement?
backText: It allows the program to break or continue for a specific loop within a group of nested loops.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.054
frontText: What does this code print? String s = "hmm"; System.out.println(s.substring(1, 2));
backText: m ‐ substring starts with the character at index 1 (m) and ends with the character before index 2.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.055
frontText: What does this code print? String s = "hmm"; s.substring(1); System.out.println(s);
backText: hmm The result of substring() is not stored anywhere, and strings are immutable, so s itself is not saved.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.056
frontText: Which of the following StringBuilder methods can be chained? append(), delete(), insert(), reverse(), substring(), toString()
backText: append(), delete(), insert() and reverse() can be chained because they return a StringBuilder. The other two return a String.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.057
frontText: What is in the StringBuilder created by System.out.println(new StringBuilder("surprise").insert(3, "!!").replace(1, 3, "-"));?
backText: s-!!prise

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.058
frontText: _____ is used to reliably check if two String values are the same.
backText: equals()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.059
frontText: How many objects are created in String[] s = new String[5];?
backText: Just one. The references are all set to null by default.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.060
frontText: Write a line of code to print the number of elements in this: int abc[] = new int[9];
backText: System.out.println(abc.length);

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.061
frontText: Write a line of code to print both the first and last index of this array: boolean[] b = {true, false};
backText: System.out.println(b[0] + " " + b[b.length - 1]); or System.out.println(b[0] + " " + b[1]);

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.062
frontText: What does the following output? int[] x = { 7, 8, 9}; int[] y = { 7, 7, 7}; System.out.println(Arrays.compare(x, y) + " " + Arrays.mismatch(x, y));
backText: 1 1

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.063
frontText: How would you create a new list and add the value true to it?
backText: List list = new ArrayList<>(); list.add(true);

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.064
frontText: What functional interface does Java provide that declares a single method that returns a boolean?
backText: Predicate

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.065
frontText: Which characters in this statement are optional? (a) -> { return true; }
backText: The parentheses, braces, return statement, and semicolon. It could have been a->true.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.066
frontText: Which characters in this statement are optional? () -> { System.out.println(); return true; }
backText: None. The parentheses are required when there aren’t any parameters. The braces are required because there are multiple statements.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.067
frontText: What functional interface does Java provide for that compares two values?
backText: Comparator

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.068
frontText: What functional interface does Java provide that doesn’t take any parameters?
backText: Supplier

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.069
frontText: What functional interface does Java provide returns void?
backText: Consumer

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.070
frontText: Which of the following can removeIf() be called on? List/Map/Set
backText: List

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.071
frontText: Which of the following can sort() be called on? List/Map/Set
backText: List

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.072
frontText: What term describes the scenario where a local variable would be final if it would compile by adding final modifier?
backText: Effectively final

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.073
frontText: How many unimplemented methods can a functional interface have?
backText: One

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.074
frontText: What method would you use on ArrayList if you wanted to pass a lambda and print each value on its own line?
backText: forEach()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.075
frontText: True or false? An instance method is allowed to reference a static variable.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.076
frontText: True or false? A static method is allowed to reference an instance variable.
backText: False (except through a reference to a class instance)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.077
frontText: Write a static import to import the static LENGTH variable of a.b.C
backText: import static a.b.C.LENGTH; or import static a.b.C.*;

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.078
frontText: True or false? Overloaded methods have the same method signatures.
backText: False. The parameter lists must be different.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.079
frontText: Which of the following may be different in an overloaded method: method name, return type, access modifier, exception list?
backText: The return type, access modifier, and exception list may vary. If the method name were different, it would be a different method rather than an overloaded method.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.080
frontText: Which order does Java use when looking for matches in overloaded methods of autoboxing, exact match, widening primitives, and varargs?
backText: Exact match, widening primitives, autoboxing, varargs

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.081
frontText: List the six parts of a method declaration in order (not including the exception clause).
backText: Access modifiers, optional specifiers, return type, method name, parameter list, method body

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.082
frontText: List all the access modifiers in Java.
backText: public, private, protected, and default. The first three are keywords in Java. The last is specified with the lack of a keyword.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.083
frontText: When is a return statement not required in a method?
backText: When the return type is void

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.084
frontText: What is wrong with public void method(String... s, int... b) {}?
backText: A vararg parameter must be the last parameter in a parameter list, and only one is allowed per method.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.085
frontText: In an encapsulated class, instance variables are of ___________ scope and getters/setters are of ____________ scope.
backText: private, public

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.086
frontText: True or false? Objects in Java can inherit at most one class.
backText: False. While Java does rely on single inheritance, a class can extend another class, so a single class may inherit multiple classes.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.087
frontText: What keyword can be used to access a member of parent class?
backText: super

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.088
frontText: True or false? Every compiled class has a constructor.
backText: True. The compiler will insert a default no‐argument constructor if none is explicitly written by the developer.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.089
frontText: Which instance fields in a class must be initialized exactly once? Name the three places they can be initialized.
backText: final fields. They can be initialized in the line in which they are declared, in an instance initializer, or in a constructor.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.090
frontText: List the order of class and instance initialization within a single class.
backText: static variables declarations, static initializers, instance variable declarations, instance initializers, constructors

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.091
frontText: True or false? The this() statement can be used to call other constructors within the class but can be used only on the first line of a constructor.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.092
frontText: Name the four rules an overridden method must follow.
backText: An overridden method must have the same signature, the same or a more accessible access modifier, and a covariant return type. It also must not throw a new or broader checked exception.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.093
frontText: A method with a generic return type may be overridden provided the return type and generic parameter meet what criteria?
backText: The return type is covariant, and the generic parameter is the same.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.094
frontText: Fill in the blanks with redeclared, overridden, or hidden: A protected instance method can be _________ by a subclass, a static method can be _________ by a subclass, a variable can be _________ by a subclass, and a private method can be _________ in a subclass.
backText: A protected instance method can be overridden by a subclass, a static method can be hidden by a subclass, a variable can be hidden by a subclass, and a private method can be redeclared in a subclass.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.095
frontText: In which situations does the compiler refrain from or report an error trying to insert a default no‐argument constructor?
backText: If the class has at least one constructor declared, the compiler will not insert one. It will also throw an error trying to insert one if the parent class does not define a no‐argument constructor for the implicit super() call.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.096
frontText: Name three differences between an abstract class and interface.
backText: Any of the following are valid differences: abstract classes can contain regular instance methods and variables, abstract classes have constructors, abstract classes can contain instance and static initializers, interfaces include implicit method and type modifiers, a class can extend only one class but and interface can extend multiple interfaces, a class can implement multiple interfaces, interfaces can include default methods, interfaces have special rules around access modifiers and methods, interfaces can only contain public static final variables.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.097
frontText: What modifiers are implicitly applied to all interface variables?
backText: public, static, and final

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.098
frontText: True or false? An interface can extend multiple interfaces.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.099
frontText: Which method modifiers cannot be used with abstract?
backText: static, private, and final

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.100
frontText: Fill in the blank: A _______ class is the first nonabstract class that extends an abstract class and is required to implement all inherited abstract methods.
backText: concrete

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.101
frontText: What modifiers are implicitly applied to all interface methods without a body?
backText: public and abstract

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.102
frontText: True or false? Polymorphism allows an object to be passed as a class it inherits, but not an interface type.
backText: False. Polymorphism allows an object to be passed by any reference type that the class inherits.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.103
frontText: What access modifiers can be applied to a member inner class?
backText: public, protected, default (package‐private), and private

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.104
frontText: True or false? A class can implement two interfaces that have the same method signature.
backText: True, provided the methods are compatible using the rules for overridden methods

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.105
frontText: Fill in the blank: An abstract method must be _______ in the first concrete subclass that inherits the method.
backText: overridden

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.106
frontText: What is the parent class for all exception and error types in Java?
backText: Throwable

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.107
frontText: What exception class should never be handled or declared in a program?
backText: Error and Throwable

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.108
frontText: What is the difference between a checked and an unchecked exception?
backText: A checked exception must be handled or declared in the method where it is used, while an unchecked exception may be optionally handled or declared.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.109
frontText: Define the handle or declare rule and how it is implemented.
backText: The handle or declare rule applies to checked exceptions and requires the developer to either wrap the exception in a try/catch block (handle) or throw the exception to the caller (declare) using the throws keyword in the method declaration.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.110
frontText: What type of statement is used to ensure a file is always closed after it is used?
backText: A try‐with‐resources statement. While this could be also accomplished with a finally block, the try‐with‐resources statement is far more concise.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.111
frontText: True or false? A multi‐catch expression can accept any pairs of exception types.
backText: False. A multi‐catch expression will fail to compile if one of the exception types is a subclass of another.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.112
frontText: Given the following five exception classes, indicate which are checked exceptions and which are unchecked exceptions: ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException, ExceptionInInitializerError, FileNotFoundException, ClassCastException, NumberFormatException
backText: All of them are unchecked exceptions, except FileNotFoundException, which is a checked exception.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.113
frontText: True or false? A try block can have at most one associated catch block.
backText: False. A try block can have zero or more catch blocks, provided the exception types of each subsequent catch block is not a subtype of the exceptions in a previous catch block.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.114
frontText: What interface and method must a class implement to be used in a try‐with‐resources expression?
backText: The Autocloseable interface with the void close() method.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.115
frontText: What is a stack trace and how is it useful in exception handling?
backText: A stack trace shows all of the methods on the stack when an exception is thrown. It can be printed at runtime and used to trace the cause of an exception.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.116
frontText: What is the name of the file that must be in the root directory of your module?
backText: module-info.java

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.117
frontText: What keyword in the module‐info is used to specify that calling code can use a package?
backText: exports

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.118
frontText: What keyword in the module‐info is used to specify that the module calls code in another module?
backText: requires

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.119
frontText: What program comes with the JDK for listing the modules a jar depends on?
backText: jdeps

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.120
frontText: When running a Java modular program, what character separates the module name and fully qualified class name?
backText: /

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.121
frontText: What are the short and long forms of the java command used for the module path?
backText: -p and --module-path

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.122
frontText: What module is automatically made available to all other modules?
backText: java.base

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.123
frontText: What goes in the module‐info to specify that modules requiring your module can access specific other modules?
backText: requires transitive

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.124
frontText: What can you pass to the java command to view the modules when running a program?
backText: --show-module-resolution

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.125
frontText: True or false? A Java program can use a mix of modular JARs and non‐modular JARs.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f1.126
frontText: True or false? If a module doesn’t contain a module‐info file, one is automatically generated.
backText: False

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.001
frontText: What parameter types are allowed in a main() method?
backText: String[] or String...

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.002
frontText: True or false? A class can be compiled and executed in a one command.
backText: True. Java now supports single‐file source‐code programs.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.003
frontText: What is a redundant package import?
backText: A package import that is unnecessary. Removing the import does not prevent the code from compiling.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.004
frontText: What are the names of the options available to set a class path in a java or javac command?
backText: -cp, --classpath, and -class-path

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.005
frontText: What is the name of the option available to set an output directory in a javac command?
backText: -d

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.006
frontText: Fill in the blank: When executing a jar command, _____ is used to specify the JAR should be created, while _____ is used to specify the directory used to create the JAR.
backText: Lowercase -c is used to specify that the JAR should be created, while uppercase -C is used to specify the directory used to create the JAR.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.007
frontText: Which of the following are valid literals? double d1 =1_234; double d2 = 5_.6; double d3 = 7_8.9_0; double d4 =1.0_;
backText: Only 1_234 and 7_8.9_0 are valid literals. The other two have an underscore (_) next to a decimal or at the end of the value.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.008
frontText: Which of the following are reserved words in Java? not, super, try, again, news, triple, synchronize
backText: super, try

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.009
frontText: What is wrong with the following statement? int x, long y;
backText: Variables declared together in a single statement must have the same type.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.010
frontText: What is the syntax of a case statement?
backText: case <value> : <expression>

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.011
frontText: What is the maximum number of nested loops an expression can have?
backText: There is no set limit.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.012
frontText: What three statements can be used to execute a loop early?
backText: continue, break, return

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.013
frontText: What is the data type of z? int x = 1; double y = 5; var z = y * z;
backText: Trick question! The code does not compile because z is on the left and right‐hand sides of an assignment.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.014
frontText: Describe the parts of a traditional for loop.
backText: A traditional for loop contains three parts: an initialization block called at the start of the loop, a conditional statement used to determine whether the loop should continue, and an update statement called after each iteration of the loop body.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.015
frontText: Describe the parts of a for‐each loop.
backText: A for‐each loop contains two parts: a variable declaration (type and name) and an object to iterate over, which can be an array or class that implements java.lang.Iterable.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.016
frontText: What String method returns the position of a value in a String?
backText: indexOf()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.017
frontText: What String method returns true if a value is present within a String?
backText: contains()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.018
frontText: What does immutable mean?
backText: Immutable means an object cannot be modified after it is created, such as a String object.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.019
frontText: What method removes a character within a StringBuilder object?
backText: deleteCharAt()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.020
frontText: What does the following expression return? new StringBuilder("Hello").equals("Hello")
backText: False, as they are not the same object type

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.021
frontText: Write a statement to create a three‐dimensional primitive integer array initialized with the values [1 2] [3 4].
backText: int[][] array = {{1,2}, {3,4}};

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.022
frontText: What method is used to replace a value of an element in a List?
backText: set(int index, String element)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.023
frontText: What method is used to remove all elements of a List or ArrayList?
backText: clear()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.024
frontText: Name two advantages of using a numeric wrapper class for a variable over using a primitive type.
backText: The value of the variable can be set to null, and the variable can be used in a generic collection or type.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.025
frontText: Fill in the blank: _____ is the process by which a wrapper value is automatically converted to a primitive type, while _____ is the process by which a primitive value is automatically converted to a wrapper type.
backText: Unboxing, autoboxing

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.026
frontText: How do you specify a method may accept zero or many arguments?
backText: Use a vararg expression, such as String... myArgs

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.027
frontText: Which collections type would you use to track the number of unique visitors to a zoo in a year?
backText: Set

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.028
frontText: What class contains the min() and max() methods, for which the package containing the class is automatically imported into every Java program?
backText: java.lang.Math

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.029
frontText: What are the pow() and round() methods?
backText: The pow() method computes the exponent of a value to a power, while the round() method gets rid of the decimal point after an integer value, rounding up if the value is 0.5 or higher and down otherwise.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.030
frontText: True or false? The following is a valid lambda expression: (final var apples) -> {return true;}
backText: True. It can refer to a Predicate with a generic type.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.031
frontText: Which interface is used to declare a custom sort on an arbitrary class?
backText: Comparator. Note that Comparable would be used to define a sort as part of the class definition.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.032
frontText: Given a List object and the sort operation using natural comparison, how would the following values be sorted? 12, Dog, cat, 1, Monkey
backText: 1, 12, Dog, Monkey, cat

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.033
frontText: Which built‐in functional interface(s) use the test(Object obj) method?
backText: Predicate

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.034
frontText: Describe the Collection removeIf() operation including the parameters it takes.
backText: The removeIf() operation takes a Predicate and removes all elements from a Collection for which the Predicate evaluates to true.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.035
frontText: What parameter type does Collection forEach() take?
backText: Consumer

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.036
frontText: What aspects of the following statement are invalid? Consumer p = (p) -> {int var = 3; var++; return;};
backText: The p variable is reused inside the lambda expression. The rest of the statement is valid.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.037
frontText: What do overloaded and override mean, as they pertain to methods?
backText: An overloaded method has the same method name but different parameters, while an overridden method has the same method name and the same parameters. Both may have different return types or declare different exceptions, although overridden methods must follow certain rules to do so.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.038
frontText: What must appear immediately before a method name?
backText: The return type

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.039
frontText: Which has a less restrictive access, protected or default (package‐private)?
backText: protected since it can be accessed by a subclass or a member in the same package.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.040
frontText: True or false? A static variable must be declared final and public.
backText: False. That restriction applies only to static variables declared inside an interface.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.041
frontText: True or false? Through autoboxing, an int[] array will be automatically converted to an Integer[] array.
backText: False. Autoboxing and unboxing do not apply to arrays, only primitive types.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.042
frontText: What is encapsulation in Java?
backText: Encapsulation means the state not available to callers of the object. This is commonly implemented by marking all instance variables private.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.043
frontText: How do you modify an int variable passed to a method so that the caller of the method sees any changes in the value?
backText: This cannot be done directly since Java is a pass‐by‐value language. The only way for the caller to see changes is to pass the int value inside an object type, such as an array, or send it back as the return value of the method.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.044
frontText: How many exceptions can a method declare?
backText: Zero to many exceptions can be declared; there is no set limit.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.045
frontText: What class do all instances inherit from?
backText: java.lang.Object

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.046
frontText: What is an overloaded constructor?
backText: When a class declares more than one constructor, they are referred to as overloaded constructors since they have the same implicit name but different method parameters.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.047
frontText: True or false? A comment may appear on a line in a constructor before super() or this() is called.
backText: True, as comments are not counted as statements, which would not be allowed before a call to this() or super() in a constructor

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.048
frontText: How many arguments can a default constructor take?
backText: It always takes zero arguments.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.049
frontText: What type of exceptions is an overridden method allowed to declare?
backText: An overridden method may declare new unchecked exceptions, although not any new checked exceptions. It may also declare a checked exception type that is narrower than the method it inherits or none at all.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.050
frontText: Given an overridden method with a method parameter of ArrayList, what possible type(s) does a method overriding it have?
backText: Only ArrayList. Change the argument type from ArrayList causes the overridden method to become an overloaded method. Changing the generic type from String is considered an invalid override.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.051
frontText: Suppose you have a child class that overrides a method and has a return type of ArrayList. What possible return type (or types) does the method it is overriding have?
backText: Any supertype of ArrayList is valid, such as List or Collection. It could also be the same type, ArrayList. The generic type String must be the same, though.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.052
frontText: What exception is thrown if class cannot be referenced as another type at runtime?
backText: ClassCastException

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.053
frontText: Name at least three places the final modifier can be used.
backText: On a class/method declaration, on an instance/static variable, on a constructor/method argument, or on a local variable

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.054
frontText: True or false? The type of var is known at compile time.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.055
frontText: How do you create an instance of an interface?
backText: You must first define a class that implements the interface and then instantiate the class.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.056
frontText: True or false? One way to create a utility class that no one can instantiate is to declare it abstract and final.
backText: False. A class cannot be marked both abstract and final. A utility class that no one can instantiate is commonly marked final and declared with a private constructor.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.057
frontText: The instanceof operator may be used with which of the following types: interfaces, primitives, abstract classes, concrete classes, arrays?
backText: Interfaces, abstract classes, concrete classes, arrays (all but primitives)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.058
frontText: What is the syntax for declaring an abstract method?
backText: The method declaration contains the abstract keyword, and the method body {} is replaced with a semicolon (;) indicating the implementation is omitted.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.059
frontText: What is polymorphism in Java?
backText: It is the property of an object to take on many different forms.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.060
frontText: What modifiers are top‐level types permitted to have in Java?
backText: public and default (package‐private)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.061
frontText: Fill in the blank: A(n) ________ cannot be instantiated in Java.
backText: abstract class or interface (either is correct)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.062
frontText: What is the purpose of a try‐with‐resources statement?
backText: A try‐with‐resources statement ensures a resource is automatically closed when it is no longer used.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.063
frontText: Given a try block with no finally, what is the syntax of a multi‐catch expression?
backText: try { ... } catch (Exception1 | ... | Exceptionn e) { ... }

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.064
frontText: Name two ways to see the output of an exception.
backText: Calling printStackTrace() or toString() on the exception class

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.065
frontText: True or false? Error is an unchecked exception.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.066
frontText: What specific exception class is often thrown when an infinite recursion mistake has been made?
backText: StackOverflowError

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.067
frontText: What specific exception class is thrown when a number is divided by zero?
backText: ArithmeticException

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.068
frontText: What specific exception class is thrown when a reference variable that has not been assigned is used?
backText: NullPointerException

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.069
frontText: What is the short and long form of the java command option used to describe the details of a module?
backText: -d and --describe-module

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.070
frontText: What can you pass to the java command option to view the modules without running the program?
backText: --list-modules

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.071
frontText: What is the short and long form of the jar command option used to make a new JAR file?
backText: -c and --create

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.072
frontText: What is the short and long form of the jdeps command option used to summarize the details of a module?
backText: -s and --summary

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.073
frontText: What is the name of the method that guarantees the garbage collector will run?
backText: Trick question! System.gc() suggests that the garbage collector run but does not guarantee it.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.074
frontText: Is this a constructor or a method? public void MyClass() { }
backText: It is a method (not a constructor) because it has a return type.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.075
frontText: Write a java command that executes the Skynet class, passing Start process as a single parameter.
backText: java Skynet "Start process"

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.076
frontText: What does the diamond operator, <>, do?
backText: The diamond operator <> is used on the right‐hand side of assignment to infer the generic type from the left‐hand side.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.077
frontText: How do you call one constructor from another in the same class?
backText: this()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.078
frontText: What common interface can this lambda expression by assigned to? pi -> System.out.println()
backText: Consumer, as it takes a generic value and returns void

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.079
frontText: What common interface can this lambda expression be assigned to? () -> 3.14159
backText: Supplier, as it takes no method arguments and returns a value. More specifically, it is a DoubleSupplier.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.080
frontText: What is the type of myData in the following statements? List data = new ArrayList(); for(var myData : data) {}
backText: The type is Object, as List does not include a generic argument

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.081
frontText: How do you override a private method in an abstract subclass?
backText: You cannot override a private method in any subclass, abstract or otherwise. You can redeclare them, although they are not inherited.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.082
frontText: What is a covariant return type?
backText: Given an overridden method and the method it inherits, the return of both must be void, or the return type of the overridden method must be a subtype of the return type of the inherited method.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.083
frontText: True or false? An abstract class that implements an interface is not required to implement any of the interface’s abstract methods.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.084
frontText: When are you required to call super() in your constructor?
backText: You are required when not calling this() and the parent class does not define a default no‐argument constructor.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.085
frontText: Name three advantages of using modules.
backText: Any of the following: better access control by restricting access to only named packages, clearer dependency management, custom or minimal JRE builds, improved performance, unique package enforcement, avoiding JAR hell

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.086
frontText: When defining a class it its own file, what parts are optional?
backText: The package and import statements are optional. The class declaration is not.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.087
frontText: Order the following operators in decreasing order of precedence: * ==
backText: * ==

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.088
frontText: How many default statements can a switch statement contain?
backText: A switch statement can have zero or one default statements.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.089
frontText: How many case statements can a switch statement contain?
backText: Barring any VM limits, there is no limit to the number of case statements that a switch statement can have, provided the constant value of each case statement is unique.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.090
frontText: How can ternary operators lead to unperformed side effects?
backText: Only one of the two right‐hand expressions of a ternary operator is evaluated at runtime. Including an expression that modifies a value, such as x++, may lead to it not being performed at runtime.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.091
frontText: Is var a reserved word in Java?
backText: No, but it is a reserved type name. It can be used as an identifier but not a class or interface name.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.092
frontText: True or false? A switch statement can use a var, provided the var is marked final.
backText: False. A switch statement can use a var, provided the var resolves to one of the acceptable switch expression types.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.093
frontText: What is a static import statement, and when is it commonly used?
backText: A static import is a special type of import statement for static members of a class, such as a static variable or static method. They are commonly used when the same variable or method is accessed repeatedly in a class.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.094
frontText: What is the value of e in this statement: Float e = 2.71828;?
backText: Trick question! The code does not compile as the expression is promoted to double first, which cannot be boxed to Float.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.095
frontText: What methods are inherited in a subclass?
backText: Methods marked public and protected are inherited by a subclass. If the two classes are in the same package, then default (package‐private) methods are also inherited.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.096
frontText: How are numeric and String values evaluated when used together in a set of concatenation operations?
backText: Excluding overriding order of operation with parentheses, the values are evaluated from left to right. If the two values are both numbers, then they are added together. If one of the two values is a String, then the numeric value is converted to a String, and string concatenation is performed on the two values.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.097
frontText: Name two ways you can check whether two String values are the same excluding their case.
backText: You can call equalsIgnoreCase() to check for equality excluding case. You can also call equals() on the result of calling toUpperCase() or toLowerCase() on both values.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.098
frontText: Which built‐in method can be used to check whether the end of a String value contains a suffix?
backText: endsWith()

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.099
frontText: What method can be used to properly compare two String values using == even if one of the values has been created with the new keyword?
backText: Calling intern() on each value before using it in an == expression ensures both values come from the String pool and will return true when they are same.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.100
frontText: True or false? Call String.createPool() on startup to properly initialize the String pool.
backText: False. The String is created and managed by the JVM automatically.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.101
frontText: What packages are imported by default?
backText: Only the package java.lang is imported by default. It contains many classes.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.102
frontText: If a try statement has both a catch block and a finally block, which order do they run in if an exception is thrown?
backText: try followed by catch followed by finally

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.103
frontText: If a try statement has both a catch block and a finally block, which order do they run in if an exception is not thrown?
backText: try followed by finally

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.104
frontText: Is a class that extends RuntimeException a checked or unchecked exception?
backText: Unchecked

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.105
frontText: How do you call this method from another class? public class StaticMethod { public static void callMe() { } }
backText: StaticMethod.callMe();

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.106
frontText: What does System.out.println(1 + 2 + "3" + 4 + 5); print?
backText: 3345. It is evaluated as 1 + 2 becomes 3, then 3 + "3" becomes "33", then "33" + 4 becomes "334", and finally "334" + 5 becomes "3345". The quotes aren’t printed.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.107
frontText: True or false? For inherited methods of the parent class, both super and this can be used interchangeably within a child class to access a method, assuming the child class does not override it.
backText: True

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.108
frontText: What modifier(s) do all members of an interface implicitly have?
backText: public

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.109
frontText: True or false? An interface is a type of abstract class.
backText: False. While an interface shares many properties of an abstract class, it is not actually an abstract class.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.110
frontText: What code can call the method void print() {}?
backText: Code in the same package

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.111
frontText: What code can read protected String s?
backText: Code in the same package or code that subclasses the class containing that instance variable

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.112
frontText: A regular try statement (not try‐with‐resources) is required to have how many catch blocks?
backText: Zero if it has a finally block; one otherwise

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.113
frontText: In a try‐with‐resources statement, which is executed first: the implicit close() method or a programmer declared catch block?
backText: The implicit close() is always executed as soon as the try block is complete, before any programmer defined catch or finally blocks are executed.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.114
frontText: When do you use the throw and throws keywords?
backText: throw is used when throwing an exception. throws is used in a method declaration.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.115
frontText: ______ is used when comparing variables to see whether they point to the same object.
backText: ==

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.116
frontText: What keyword would be used for a class that uses an interface?
backText: implements

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.117
frontText: True or false? A reference to a class may be automatically used as a reference to a subclass without an explicit cast.
backText: False. A reference to a class may be automatically used as a reference to a superclass without an explicit cast.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.118
frontText: What single character, allowed in a variable identifier, may not be used as an identifier by itself?
backText: A single underscore (_) cannot be used as an identifier.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.119
frontText: What character separates parameters in a parameter list?
backText: A comma (,)

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.120
frontText: What code can call private methods?
backText: Code in the same class

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.121
frontText: Which of the following classes do import a.b.* actually import: a.A, a.b.B, a.b.c.C?
backText: Only a.b.B. The import wildcard only matches in that package directly, not subpackages.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.122
frontText: Which variables may have a scope smaller than a method: class, local, or instance?
backText: Local

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.123
frontText: Which variables are in scope for the entire program: class, local, or instance?
backText: Class

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.124
frontText: Which variables require the programmer to initialize them before use: class, local, or instance?
backText: Local

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.125
frontText: Where in a switch statement does the default block need to go?
backText: The default block can appear anywhere in the switch statement, including the beginning, middle, and end.

title: fc584704.JaSE11PrgISG.f2.126
frontText: If you want the new value of an increment operator to be used in an expression after it is updated, which operator would you use?
backText: The pre‐increment operator, as in ++x
